Decisions, Decisions: Key Issues to Consider in Selecting a Field Service Management Solution 

Mobility in the Manufacturing Workplace: 8 Must-have Mobile Application Qualities to Increase Operational Efficiency 

 



General Motors emerged from a prepackaged, government backed Chapter 11 bankruptcy in mid-2009 as “the new GM,” or, more precisely, NGMCO, Inc. Prior to that, the automaker suffered through years of losses that brought it to the point of extinction.To prevent a repeat, CEO Dan Ackerson, who took the helm in August 2010, knows that the new GM can’t look much like its pre-bankruptcy self. It needs to be nimble, streamlined, and globally integrated, while producing reliable, fuel efficient cars that can meet and beat foreign competitors--especially in fast-growing emerging markets.The strategy looks good on paper, but meaningless unless Akerson and his team can execute. Enter Senior VP and CIO Randy Mott, who joined the automaker in February 2012 after leading IT departments at global giants such as Hewlett-Packard, Dell, and Wal-Mart.Mott’s mission: Drive an IT transformation that aligns with and supports GM’s business revamp. “To drive the overall business transformation, we needed to build an IT organization that could support and enable rapid innovation,” said Mott, in an exclusive interview with CruxialCIO.Mott’s first priority on coming aboard was to turn GM’s IT department from one that depended mostly on outsourcing contractors for key projects to one that got things done in-house. Mott’s predecessor, Ralph Szygenda, was a big believer in outsourcing, and relied heavily on vendors like Electronic Data Systems (now part of Hewlett-Packard), AT&T, Cap Gemini, Accenture, and Wipro Technologies.Szygenda insisted that his “dream team” operate globally, and use standards-based approaches to IT service delivery. Their playbooks had to include ITIL, CMM, Six Sigma and other standards to ensure that, for instance, both EDS’ and Accenture’s approach to provisioning were compatible.But Mott says that doesn’t go far enough for a company that needs to rapidly innovate. “Part of the premise for innovation and application change is that you implement projects. And implementing projects into an outsourced environment is by definition hard, costly, and slow.”So shortly after his arrival, Mott cut ties with the bulk of GM’s contractors, and began the process of bringing projects back to Michigan. In the process, the company’s IT staff expanded from 1,400 to more than 7,000 workers. GM is also investing $546 million in a new technology infrastructure.GM’s transformation also includes an effort to collect and make better use of the vast amount of data that it collects from its operations. It’s building an Enterprise Data Warehouse to centralize and standardize information gathered from company operations across the globe. It’s harvesting data from the manufacturing floor to support a quality initiative led by senior VP Alicia Boler-Davis, and it’s culling bits and bytes that come in through customer-facing services like OnStar. “Every piece of transactional data gives us an opportunity to improve,” says Mott.Post-bailout GM needs to be lean, mean, and efficient. That applies to its IT unit. Among the efficiency projects that Mott is pursuing is data center consolidation. The company is trimming its IT real estate footprint from 23 datacenters to just two. There’s the recently opened, 5,040 square-foot facility in Warren, Mich., and a new datacenter that will come online next year at its vehicle proving ground in Milford, Mich.Mott also wants to drive efficiency into his IT department by automating routine processes, such as provisioning and network monitoring. That will save the company money, and also frees up staff to work on projects that drive business value for General Motors. Prior to his arrival, Mott says about 75% of GM’s IT personnel, whether company employees or outsourced contractors, were engaged in routine, keep-the-servers-up type of work, while only 25% were engaged in truly innovative projects. Mott wants to flip that, to the point where 80% are driving innovation. “We need to change the mix,” says Mott. 










 




    Corporate Renaissance: Like the old GM, the new GM remains headquartered in downtown Detroit.  GM

 





Case Studies


COLUMBIA SPORTSWEAR: Benefiting Through Cloud 

H.B FULLER: Upgrading HR Systems 

 
White Papers


The Consumer IT Revolution 

Cloud First: Not Just Transformation, But Innovation 

 



Mott’s vision for a more efficient, streamlined, and innovative IT organization for GM sounded good in theory, but he had to execute. That required careful planning, lots of backup plans, and flawless execution. “We’ve got a $150 billion business we don’t want to interrupt,” says Mott.Insourcing. GM’s insourcing initiative involved eliminating roughly 30 vendor contracts and moving the work in-house—everything from mainframe operations and application development, to network management. Mott says the transition was eased by the fact that he automated some of the work rather than hand it off to new, in-house teams. “When you do that you take a lot of the work out of the process; it’s move and automate.”Recruitment. GM’s insourcing initiative resulted in the company’s internal IT workforce expanding from 1,400 tech pros to more than 7,000. In an era when even tech giants like Microsoft complain that it’s hard to find individuals with the skills they need, GM required a strategy for recruiting and retention. One tactic the company used was to go to where the talent is. The automaker’s four innovation centers--one is co-located at the Warren data center, the others are in Roswell, Georgia, Austin, Texas, and Chandler Arizona--put it within a 500 mile radius of 75% of the available talent in the U.S. according to Mott. “We tried to go where they are,” says Mott. “The new GM has also earned a reputation for our product design and engineering and winning in the marketplace; that’s also appealing to candidates.”GM also hired a number of employees that previously worked for its contractors, including 3,000 from HP.Consolidation. GM is moving from 23 data centers to just two, in Warren and Milford, Michigan. Such moves can be fraught with risk. Data can be lost, key applications can become unavailable, and network systems can be disrupted. “The key is that if we have any kind of problem we just don’t go,” says Mott. “We protect the business that way.” Among other things, GM moved applications that had been running on an outsourced mainframe at a Hewlett-Packard facility in Plano, Texas to a new mainframe at Warren. “We did it over two weekends; we did dry runs and dress rehearsals as this touched factories all over the world.”Big Data and analytics. GM’s IT transformation includes building a platform that allows the company to glean business insights—at a granular level—from incoming data from factory floors and customer-facing apps and services. Mott says choosing the right technology is key. At the heart of GM’s Big Data platform is Hadoop, a flexible, open-source architecture that ropes together hundreds of industry-standard servers to form a Big Data hive. GM previously ran 200 data marts. By year’s end, it will have moved 40 of those into the new architecture. “We can now invest very high volumes of data into the new data platform,” says Mott.GM’s growing Enterprise Data Warehouse also relies on IBM Infosphere BigInsights for building Hadoop applications, and reporting and analytics tools from Teradata.Private clouds. GM’s new IT infrastructure makes use of cloud principles like virtualization, shared services, load balancing and standardization. It all makes for a more efficient, cost effective environment. Mott, however, is not about to put any of GM’s applications in public or vendor-run clouds. “A lot of people who are promoting these off premises clouds are really promoting outsourcing by a different name and I think it will have all the same problems in terms of how do you stay current, how do you add to it, and how do you remain responsive to the business,” says Mott. “I’m not looking to go back.”  










 




    IT believer: Like his CIO Randy Mott, GM CEO Dan Akerson thinks key tech systems belong in house.  Reuters

 





Case Studies


D7 CONSULTING: Upgrading Software to Office 365 

STONE GATE SENIOR LIVING: 2,800% ROI Tracking Overtime 

 
White Papers


In-memory Computing: Lifting the Burden of Big Data 

Shifting Sands: Semiconductor Makers Face New Challenges as Momentum Moves from Developed Economies to Emerging Markets 

 



GM CIO Randy Mott is not overhauling the company’s global tech footprint just for the sake of change. The IT transformation parallels an overall business transformation that CEO Dan Akerson has been driving since he was named to the top job in 2010.Akerson wants to make GM a nimble, efficient, innovative company with a consistent, worldwide footprint. By 2015, he wants 65% of GM’s auto manufacturing on global platforms. And, of course, he wants the automaker to be consistently profitable. There’s little chance, as in zero, that the company would get another bailout from the federal government.Mott’s role is to create an IT environment that supports and enables Akerson’s goals. “We needed a different mix in terms of how much innovation we do and how do we grow our business. You take that with all the other GM initiatives going on from a business standpoint and that was the mission, starting two years ago, and we’re still executing on it today.”Akerson himself is a big believer in GM owning its own tech infrastructure. “You have to own it and you have to control it and when you don’t, you’re at the whim of other companies and their priorities, and if they have financial problems, their difficulties,” the CEO said earlier this year at a press conference to open the Warren tech center.One example of how GM’s IT unit is supporting company goals is a new service that helps the automaker and its customers connect more easily. Salespeople, and even consumers, can walk the lot at GM dealers and use a mobile app, for the Apple iPad or smartphones, that provides deep-dive information on the vehicle the user is looking at. “It offers a richer experience for the customer and helps them with what may be a large purchasing decision in their lives,” says Mott.There’s evidence that GM’s transformation, including the IT part, is starting to pay off. The company’s stock price has increased from a $19.36 on July 20 of last year, to $37.36 on Nov. 22 of last week, a gain of 93%.And the company is profitable. It posted net income of $0.7 billion in the third quarter on $39 billion in net revenues, up from $37.6 billion in the prior year quarter.But GM, and Mott, aren’t satisfied. Next year, the CIO plans to push even harder on the innovation front. The business value created from new projects undertaken will be three times that of what his group delivered this year. “That’s the headline for 2014,” says Mott. “We want shorter projects, and we want to deliver more projects with higher business value more quickly.”GM CEO Akerson Touts Company’s TurnaroundTheoretical Foundations Of Big Data AnalysisWhy Enterprise Data WarehouseVirtual Hierarchies To Support Server Consolidation  




